d forms (enolization)\n- The O+:23 (oxocarbenium oxygen) becomes a regular methoxy oxygen O:23-C\n\nThis is essentially an E1cb-like elimination at the oxocarbenium center, or more precisely, an elimination forming an enol ether from an oxocarbenium.\n\nThe reaction center atoms are: C:21, C:22, O:23, H:20, O:10\n\nBond changes:\n- C:21–H:20 broken\n- H:20–O:10 formed (proton transfer to water)\n- C:22=O+:23 changed to C:22–O:23 (bond order change from 2 to 1)\n- C:21–C:22 changed from single to double bond (bond order change from 1 to 2)\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary.\n\nThe reaction center involves 5 mapped atoms: C:21, C:22, O:23, H:20, O:10\n\nBond edits:\n1. C:21–H:20: break (bond order 1→0)\n2. O:10–H:20: form (bond order 0→1) \n3. C:22=O:23: change bond order 2→1\n4. C:21–C:22: change bond order 1→2\n\nThis is an elimination (E1cb-type) at an oxocarbenium center, producing an enol ether and protonated water."
